{
  "Archimedes' principle states that the buoyant force on an object submerged in a fluid equals:": "",
  "The pressure at the bottom of the object": "",
  "The weight of the object": "",
  "The weight of the fluid displaced by the object": "",
  "The volume of the object times gravity": "",
  "F_buoyant = rho_fluid * V_displaced * g. This equals the weight of the volume of fluid displaced by the object.": "",
  "An object floats when:": "",
  "Its volume is greater than the fluid's volume": "",
  "It is heavier than the fluid": "",
  "Its density is greater than the fluid's density": "",
  "Its density is less than or equal to the fluid's density": "",
  "If rho_object < rho_fluid, the object floats with a fraction submerged equal to rho_object/rho_fluid.": "",
  "The buoyant force on a fully submerged object depends on:": "",
  "The mass of the object": "",
  "The depth of the object": "",
  "The volume of the object and the density of the fluid": "",
  "The shape of the object only": "",
