  "What is 'Archimedes' principle'?": "",
  "Any object wholly or partially submerged in a fluid experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced": "",
  "Fluids exert pressure in all directions within the broader context of Archimedes analysis": "",
  "Pressure increases with depth, since the relevant Archimedes factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "Objects float if they are light enough according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Archimedes' principle: F_b = rho_fluid * g * V_displaced. It explains floating, sinking, and apparent weight in fluids.": "",
  "What is 'buoyant force'?": "",
  "The force pushing an object to the bottom": "",
  "The weight of an object in a fluid": "",
  "The net upward force exerted on an object by the fluid in which it is immersed, caused by pressure differences": "",
  "Surface tension pulling an object upward": "",
  "The buoyant force is the net upward force from fluid pressure acting on all surfaces of the submerged object.": "",
  "What is 'apparent weight'?": "",
  "The measured weight of an object when submerged in a fluid, equal to its actual weight minus the buoyant force": "",
  "The weight of the displaced fluid": "",
  "The actual gravitational weight of an object": "",
  "The weight an object appears to have visually": "",
  "Apparent weight = W - F_b = mg - rho_fluid*V*g. Objects feel lighter in water because buoyancy partially supports them.": "",
  "What is 'neutral buoyancy'?": "",
  "When an object is in a vacuum when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "When an object floats on the surface, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The condition when an object's average density equals the fluid density, so it neither sinks nor rises": "",
  "When no forces act on an object when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "At neutral buoyancy, the object remains suspended at any depth. Submarines and scuba divers adjust their buoyancy to achieve this.": "",
  "What is 'displaced volume'?": "",
  "The volume of the object above the waterline": "",
  "The empty space inside a hollow object": "",
  "The total volume of the container": "",
  "The volume of fluid pushed aside by an object immersed in the fluid": "",
  "Displaced volume equals the submerged portion of the object. For a fully submerged object, it equals the object's total volume.": "",
  "What is 'specific gravity' in the context of buoyancy?": "",
  "The ratio of an object's density to water's density, which determines what fraction submerges when floating": "",
  "The gravitational acceleration at a specific location": "",
  "The weight per unit volume": "",
  "The buoyant force per unit weight": "",
  "SG = rho_object/rho_water. If SG < 1, the object floats. The fraction submerged equals the SG when floating in water.": "",
  "What is a 'hydrometer'?": "",
  "An instrument that measures the density or specific gravity of a liquid by how deeply it sinks when floated in the liquid": "",
  "A device for measuring humidity, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A device for measuring water pressure within the broader context of hydrometer analysis": "",
  "A device for measuring water flow rate, as conventional hydrometer theory would suggest": "",
  "A hydrometer floats higher in denser liquids. The scale reads specific gravity directly from how deep the instrument sinks.": "",
  "What is 'draft' of a ship?": "",
  "The wind resistance of the ship, based on conventional assumptions about draft": "",
  "The height of the ship above water, particularly in the context of draft": "",
  "The depth to which a ship sinks below the waterline, determined by its weight and the buoyancy equation": "",
  "The speed of the ship, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A ship's draft increases as cargo is loaded (more weight requires more displaced water). Draft determines which harbors a ship can enter.": "",
  "What is 'ballast'?": "",
  "A type of anchor, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "The engine of a submarine according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Heavy material (often water) taken on or released to adjust an object's buoyancy and stability": "",
  "The hull of a ship when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Submarines use ballast tanks (flooding with water to sink, emptying to rise). Ships use ballast water for stability when cargo is unloaded.": "",
  "What is the 'metacenter' in naval architecture?": "",
  "The point about which a floating body oscillates when tilted, determining stability; it must be above the center of gravity for stable floating": "",
  "The center of mass of the ship, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing metacenter dynamics": "",
  "The deepest point of the hull, since the prevailing theory about metacenter would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "The center of the waterline, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual metacenter mechanisms at work": "",
  "If the metacenter is above the center of gravity, the ship is stable. If below, the ship will capsize.": "",
  "A 5 kg iron block (density 7800 kg/m^3) is submerged in water. What is its apparent weight?": "",
  "About 49.0 N": "",
  "About 42.7 N": "",
  "About 6.3 N": "",
  "About 35.0 N": "",
  "V = m/rho = 5/7800 = 6.41e-4 m^3. F_b = 1000*9.8*6.41e-4 = 6.28 N. Apparent weight = 49.0 - 6.28 = 42.7 N.": "",
  "A hot air balloon has a volume of 2800 m^3. If the outside air density is 1.2 kg/m^3 and the hot air inside has density 0.9 kg/m^3, what is the maximum payload (including balloon mass)?": "",
  "About 840 kg": "",
  "About 420 kg": "",
  "About 3360 kg": "",
  "About 2520 kg": "",
  "Net lift = (rho_outside - rho_inside)*V*g = (1.2-0.9)*2800*9.8 = 0.3*2800*9.8 = 8232 N = 840 kg.": "",
  "A crown weighs 14.7 N in air and 13.4 N in water. Is it pure gold (density 19,300 kg/m^3)?": "",
  "Yes, it matches gold's density": "",
  "Cannot be determined from this information": "",
  "No, the measured density is about 11,300 kg/m^3, suggesting it contains less dense metals": "",
  "No, it is denser than gold": "",
